# Database Best Practices

## Schema Design
- Use proper normalization (usually 3NF for transactional databases)
- Define foreign key constraints for referential integrity
- Use appropriate data types (don't store dates as strings)
- Add indexes on frequently queried columns
- Use UUIDs or auto-incrementing integers for primary keys

## Query Optimization
- Use query parameters to prevent SQL injection
- Avoid SELECT * - specify only needed columns
- Use JOINs efficiently and understand different join types
- Add indexes for WHERE clauses and JOIN conditions
- Use EXPLAIN/ANALYZE to understand query performance
- Implement pagination for large result sets

## Transactions
- Use transactions for operations that must be atomic
- Keep transactions short to avoid locks
- Understand isolation levels and use appropriate level
- Handle transaction rollback on errors
- Use database connection pooling

## Migrations
- Version all database schema changes
- Make migrations reversible when possible
- Test migrations on staging before production
- Never modify existing migrations in production
- Back up data before running migrations

## Performance
- Use caching strategically (Redis, Memcached)
- Implement read replicas for read-heavy workloads
- Archive old data to keep tables smaller
- Monitor slow queries and optimize them
- Use database-specific features wisely (stored procedures, triggers)
